## TL;DR: What Every Elongated Cushion Buyer Must Know First

An elongated cushion cut diamond ring pairs a cushion-shaped diamond with a length-to-width (L/W) ratio of 1.10 or higher in any ring setting — creating a finger-lengthening visual effect that a standard near-square cushion (1.00–1.05) cannot produce. Settings start at [$1,000 for the Petite Solitaire 14K White Gold](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194386?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (1,020 reviews); the best entry complete build is a lab elongated cushion at 1.5ct paired with the Petite Solitaire for approximately **$2,250 total**. **→ Best first pick: target L/W ratio 1.20 specifically — it is The Ratio Sweet Spot where elongated cushions read as distinctly elongated without losing the soft-corner cushion character that defines the shape, and the [Classic Four Prong Solitaire Platinum at $1,180](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-four-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the correct setting for it at any carat weight.**

**The Elongation Divide:** Not all cushions described as "elongated" look the same, and the L/W ratio is why. A 1.12 ratio reads as a slightly off-square stone that didn't fully commit to elongation; a 1.20 ratio reads as clearly elongated with visible finger-lengthening effect; a 1.28+ ratio begins reading as a rectangle with rounded corners rather than a cushion shape. The divide between these three visual outcomes is sharper than most buyers expect from differences measured in tenths of a decimal.

