## What Is an Elongated Cushion Cut Diamond Ring

An elongated cushion cut diamond ring is an engagement ring centered on a cushion-shaped diamond with a length-to-width ratio above 1.10 — where the stone is measurably longer than it is wide, producing a pillow-soft shape that extends toward the finger rather than sitting in a near-square outline. The elongated cushion is not a distinct diamond cut; it is the same cushion cut family (cushion brilliant or cushion modified brilliant sub-types) selected for a specific L/W ratio range. The "elongated" designation is purely about dimension selection, not cut or facet architecture.

The elongated cushion sits in a unique position among elongated fancy shapes. Ovals and pears are purpose-designed elongated cuts — their outlines are explicitly extended as part of the cutting intention. The elongated cushion is a cushion cut that happens to fall in the elongated range through cutter selection, which means buyers must specifically filter for L/W ratio when shopping, because most cushion diamond inventories include stones from 1.00 (perfectly square) to 1.30+ (strongly elongated) with no default filtering toward either end.

The elongated cushion ring category is growing rapidly as buyers discover that the elongated ratio produces a dramatically larger face-up appearance relative to carat weight than a standard square cushion. At 1.20 L/W ratio, an elongated cushion has a noticeably larger face-up visual footprint than a same-weight round brilliant, and it creates the optical finger-lengthening effect associated with elongated shapes. Both factors — visual size efficiency and finger-elongation — are driving significantly increasing demand for elongated cushions compared to the traditional near-square cushion; see our comparison in [Cushion Cut vs Round Diamond](/cushion-cut-vs-round-diamond) and the full shape profile in our [Elongated Cushion Cut Diamond guide](/elongated-cushion-cut-diamond).

