## 4-Carat Elongated Cushion Cut Diamond Ring

A 4-carat elongated cushion cut diamond ring is one of the most visually dramatic fine jewelry pieces available in the cushion format. At 1.20 L/W ratio, a 4ct elongated cushion diamond has a face-up length of approximately 11–12mm — extending across a significant portion of the finger from knuckle to knuckle on average hands. The combination of the elongated geometry and the 4ct mass creates a ring that commands visual attention in any setting and any lighting condition.

The price divide at 4ct is the sharpest in the elongated cushion category. A 4ct natural elongated cushion in F-VS1 grade from GIA currently trades [from approximately $45,000](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at Blue Nile depending on cut quality and ratio. A 4ct lab elongated cushion in F-VS1 grade from IGI trades [from approximately $5,000](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at the same quality specification — the 90%+ differential at 4ct means the 4-carat elongated cushion category is effectively dominated by lab diamonds in {{year}}.

**At 4ct, the setting selection narrows.** Standard solitaire settings sized for 1–2ct stones cannot accommodate a 4ct elongated cushion — the stone's physical dimensions (approximately 11mm × 9mm at 1.20 L/W) require a custom-sized prong head with appropriately scaled prongs. Buyers should discuss setting requirements with a Blue Nile diamond consultant before selecting a setting; the [Classic Four Prong Solitaire Platinum at $1,180](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-four-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) remains the most appropriate format at 4ct, and the platinum construction is particularly important because the heavier stone mass creates more leverage on prong tips during daily wear. Full 4ct context in our [4 Carat Cushion Cut Diamond Ring guide](/4-carat-cushion-cut-diamond-ring).

## Elongated Cushion vs Standard Cushion: Which to Choose

The choice between an elongated cushion and a standard cushion is fundamentally about two visual goals that cannot both be maximized simultaneously: pillow-softness and finger-lengthening. Standard cushions (L/W 1.00–1.05) maximize pillow-softness — from above, the stone looks equally wide as it is long, and the soft corners create a plush, balanced, near-circular impression. Elongated cushions (L/W 1.15–1.25) maximize finger-lengthening — the stone's rectangular orientation creates a visual line along the finger's length that optically extends and narrows the finger.

Neither is better; they are different products serving different aesthetic goals. Standard cushions are right for buyers who want the classic cushion aesthetic — the shape most strongly associated with the word "cushion" in jewelry, the stone that looks like a pillow or a rounded square. Elongated cushions are right for buyers who want a fancy shape with maximum finger-lengthening impact, who are considering ovals or pears but prefer cushion's soft corners over those cuts' pointed or continuously curved ends.

**Where elongated cushions have a clear, specific advantage is in face-up size efficiency.** At equal carat weight, a 1.20 L/W elongated cushion shows more face-up area than any standard cushion of the same weight — the elongated cutting style spreads the diamond's mass in two dimensions rather than concentrating it in depth. Full shape comparison in our [Cushion Cut vs Radiant Cut Diamond guide](/cushion-cut-vs-radiant-cut-diamond) and [Cushion Cut Diamond Engagement Ring guide](/cushion-cut-diamond-engagement-ring).

## Expert Summary

**The Elongation Divide is the most important concept in elongated cushion shopping** — more important than carat weight, color grade, or setting choice. The L/W ratio determines whether the buyer ends up with a ring that clearly reads as elongated (1.15+), or one that looks like a standard cushion that's slightly off-round (1.08–1.14). The single most effective action elongated cushion buyers can take is to specify a minimum L/W ratio of 1.15 in their diamond search filter and avoid anything in the 1.08–1.14 range entirely.

**The Ratio Sweet Spot (1.15–1.25) is the target zone for every elongated cushion purchase regardless of carat weight, setting, or metal.** Within this range, 1.20 is the most sought-after specific ratio — unambiguously elongated, clearly cushion in character, and the best-photographing elongated cushion ratio across all carat weights. Buyers who get to 1.20 and commit to a well-cut stone (Ideal or Very Good in natural, Excellent in lab) are making the correct elongated cushion purchase regardless of what setting or metal they choose around it.

**Lab-grown elongated cushions are where the category's best value lives.** At 2ct D-VVS1 1.20 L/W with IGI Excellent cut, a [lab elongated cushion from $2,000](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) in the [Classic Four Prong Solitaire Platinum at $1,180](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-four-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) totals from $3,180 — a complete ring that reads as the same visual product as a $15,000+ natural equivalent. See our [Blue Nile Engagement Rings Review](/blue-nile-engagement-rings-review) for full platform guidance on verifying stone quality before purchase.

> "The elongated cushion at 1.20 ratio is the most versatile fancy shape available in {{year}} — finger-lengthening, face-up size efficient, and the only fancy shape that retains the soft-corner cushion character that many buyers specifically want. The buyers I've helped who targeted 1.20 ratio deliberately rather than accepting whatever 'elongated' ratio was available are universally happy with their rings years later. The ratio discipline is what separates a good purchase from an exceptional one."
> — Farzana, Diamond Consultant

