## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is an elongated cushion cut diamond ring?

An elongated cushion cut diamond ring is an engagement ring centered on a cushion-shaped diamond with a length-to-width ratio of 1.10 or higher — where the stone is measurably longer than it is wide. At ratios of 1.15–1.25 (The Ratio Sweet Spot), the elongated cushion creates a clear finger-lengthening visual effect while retaining the soft pillow corners that define the cushion shape. It is not a different cut from a standard cushion — it is the same cushion cut family selected specifically for its L/W ratio.

### What L/W ratio is best for an elongated cushion?

1.15–1.25 is The Ratio Sweet Spot — elongated enough to read clearly and create finger-lengthening effect, not so elongated that cushion character erodes toward a rounded rectangle. Within this range, 1.20 is the single most sought-after ratio: unambiguously elongated, clearly cushion in character, and the best-photographing elongated cushion ratio across all carat weights. Avoid the 1.08–1.14 no-man's-land — stones in this range look like slightly off-square standard cushions rather than intentionally elongated ones.

### What is The Elongation Divide?

The Elongation Divide is the visual discontinuity that occurs at different L/W ratio ranges for cushion cuts. Below 1.10, cushions read as near-square with the classic pillow look; at 1.10–1.14, they fall into a no-man's-land where they read as neither clearly square nor clearly elongated; at 1.15+, they read as unambiguously elongated with the finger-lengthening effect active. The divide explains why a 0.10 difference in ratio creates a fundamentally different visual product.

### What is The Ratio Sweet Spot?

The Ratio Sweet Spot is the 1.15–1.25 L/W range where elongated cushion diamonds achieve peak performance across three criteria simultaneously: unambiguous elongation, retained cushion character, and maximum face-up size efficiency. Within this range, 1.20 is the optimal single ratio — below 1.15 elongation is ambiguous, above 1.25 cushion character degrades faster than elongation improves. Every elongated cushion diamond purchase should target this window, with 1.20 as the specific bullseye.

### How does an elongated cushion ring differ from a standard cushion ring?

Standard cushion rings (L/W 1.00–1.05) maximize the classic pillow aesthetic — the stone reads as balanced and near-square with soft corners. Elongated cushion rings (L/W 1.15–1.25) maximize finger-lengthening effect — the stone's rectangular orientation creates a visual line along the finger's length that optically extends and narrows the finger. Elongated cushions also have meaningfully larger face-up area relative to carat weight than standard cushions of the same weight.

### Is an elongated cushion similar to an oval diamond?

They share the finger-lengthening effect but are visually distinct. An oval is a purpose-designed elongated cut with a continuous curved outline — it looks like an elongated circle. An elongated cushion has a rectangular outline with four soft, distinctly cushion-style corners — it looks like a pillow stretched lengthwise, and the four-sided geometry is visible from across the room; buyers who want the elongated effect with visible corner definition should choose the elongated cushion, while buyers who prefer continuous curves should choose the oval.

### What setting works best for an elongated cushion cut diamond ring?

4-prong solitaire is the most setting-appropriate format — the four prong contacts at the four corners minimally interrupt the elongated cushion's perimeter and allow the stone's full outline to read clearly. The setting head must be sized for the stone's specific L/W ratio; a standard cushion head designed for 1.00–1.05 ratio stones will not correctly fit an elongated cushion at 1.20. The [Classic Four Prong Solitaire Platinum at $1,180](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-four-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the recommended setting at every carat weight.

### What metal should I choose for an elongated cushion ring?

White gold or platinum for F-G color stones (cool neutral metal maximizes face-up color appearance), rose gold for H-I color stones (neutralizes warmth so the stone reads white against the blush metal), yellow gold for the historically authentic cushion aesthetic and maximum color neutralization for H-I stones. Platinum is preferred over white gold for long-term durability — it requires no rhodium replating and holds prong tips longer than any karat of gold.

### How much does an elongated cushion cut diamond ring cost?

Complete builds start from approximately $2,250 (IGI 1.5ct lab elongated cushion + [Petite Solitaire 14K WG at $1,000](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194386?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)). The best-value build — IGI 2ct D-VVS1 lab 1.20 L/W + [Classic Four Prong Platinum at $1,180](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-four-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — totals from $3,180. Natural 1ct elongated cushion builds start from approximately $3,280; natural 2ct builds from approximately $10,980; lab 4ct builds from approximately $6,180.

### Are lab-grown elongated cushion diamonds worth it?

Yes — lab elongated cushions offer 70–85% price reduction versus natural equivalents at the same quality specification. At 2ct D-VVS1 1.20 L/W, a [lab elongated cushion from $2,000](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) versus a [natural equivalent from $14,000](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). The visual difference in a solitaire setting is zero — full lab context in our [Lab Grown Cushion Cut Diamond guide](/lab-grown-cushion-cut-diamond).

### Should I choose elongated cushion or radiant cut?

Elongated cushion if you want soft corners and a romantic aesthetic with finger-lengthening effect; radiant if you want sharper cut corners and maximum brilliance. The elongated cushion at 1.20 L/W and the elongated radiant are the closest visual competitors in the elongated fancy shape category — the cushion's defining edge is the soft, pillow-like corners; the radiant's defining edge is its cut-corner geometry and brighter, crisper sparkle output. Full comparison in our [Cushion Cut vs Radiant Cut Diamond guide](/cushion-cut-vs-radiant-cut-diamond).

### What carat weight works best for an elongated cushion ring?

1.5ct is the entry elongated cushion weight where the elongated outline and finger-lengthening effect are clearly visible on most hand sizes. 2ct is the sweet spot for most buyers — the stone is large enough that the elongated geometry creates unmistakable impact, and [2ct lab elongated cushions from $2,000](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) in the 1.18–1.22 L/W range are available at very accessible prices. At 3ct+, the elongated cushion becomes a statement piece — see our [2 Carat Cushion Cut Diamond Ring guide](/2-carat-cushion-cut-diamond-ring) and [1 Carat Cushion Cut Diamond Ring guide](/1-carat-cushion-cut-diamond-ring) for carat-specific size context.

### How do I shop for an elongated cushion diamond?

Use Blue Nile's [cushion diamond search](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-search?shape=cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and apply the Length to Width Ratio filter with minimum 1.15 and maximum 1.25. Sort by Excellent (lab/IGI) or Ideal/Very Good (natural/GIA) cut grade, then target 1.20 L/W ratio specifically within search results. Don't accept stones labeled "elongated" without verifying the specific ratio — the term is used loosely for everything from 1.10 to 1.35+, and the visual difference between ends of that range is substantial.

